97. da sternere] ‘grant (me) to lay low.' 98. revulsam] ‘torn back ' or ‘ open,' i. e. by the spear.

99. semiviri Phrygis] ‘the emasculate' or ‘unmanned Phrygian.' The term ‘Phrygian’ is often used by Virgil contemptuously (cf. 753 4. 103) with a suggestion of Oriental cowardice and effeminacy, and in semiviri there is also a reference to the eunuch priests of the Phrygian goddess Cybele.

In 4. ‘205 seq. the jealous Iarbas also jeers at Aeneas as ‘a perfumed Paris with his eunuch train‚' and Virgil's concep- tion of Aeneas is clearly not that of a rude and rugged warrior, but rather of a handsome cavalier whose looks did not belie his divine mother.
